<DOC><DOCNO> AP880825-0178 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-08-25-88 2126EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r p AM-Bentsen-Stocks     08-25 0211</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Bentsen-Stocks,210</SECOND><HEAD>Betsen Orders Stocks In South Africa Sold</HEAD><DATELINE>TRENTON, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Democratic vice presidential candidateLloyd Bentsen last week ordered stocks in companies doing businessin South Africa sold after finding his blind trust had invested inthem, his spokesman said Thursday.   ``He just did it'' without any prodding from anyone, spokesmanJack Devore said, confirming a report Thursday in The PatriotLedger of Quincy, Mass. The report said the Texas senator saw theblind trust stock holdings for the first time on Aug. 12, about amonth after his nomination for the vice presidency.   The newspaper report said the trust had invested $120,000 to$400,000 in the companies.   By selling the stocks, Bentsen avoided a conflict with theDemocratic Party platform, which calls for South Africa to belisted as a ``terrorist'' state and calls the nation a ``uniquelyrepressive regime.''.   The Democratic platform also promises to set a date for U.S.corporations to withdraw from South Africa.   According to Bentsen's financial disclosure form, his blindtrust included investments worth between $15,000 and $50,000 ineach of the following companies, which the state says do businessin South Africa: Caterpillar Inc., Chevron, Colgate, Palmolive,Johnson andamp; Johnson, Minnesota andamp; Manufacturing, Monsanto Co., TennecoInc., and Unisys Corp.</TEXT></DOC>